abstract = {Despite the common tendency to understand computer games as a medium somewhere between
film and traditional software, this paper argues for a more appropriate position amongst
literature. This writing explores the opportunities in analogizing digital games not
as art, but as literature. Within this framing new opportunities reveal themselves
for innovative game design and more manageable archiving of games and their relationships.
It should prove useful to media theorists, designers, and game librarians seeking
a new way to frame the analysis and production of digital games.},
