abstract = {Prototyping is critical for refining designs, but to advance to this stage requires
openness to changing ideas. We examine two cases of 14-year old children constructing
and playtesting physical prototypes of digital games: one group characterized as flexible
in their ideas, and the other characterized as fixated. Field notes, audio recordings,
and design artifacts show how one team's flexibility allowed them to discover material
constraints and affordances through prototyping; while the other's fixation influenced
